## 2. Inflation and Mortgage Interest Rates

### 2.1 Relationship Between Inflation and Interest Rates

Inflation influences mortgage rates primarily through monetary policy responses:

- Central banks, such as the Federal Reserve and the Bank of England, monitor inflation closely. When inflation rises persistently, they often increase benchmark interest rates to cool economic overheating ([Browne, 2021](https://readersdigest.co.uk/money/mortgages/how-inflation-can-increase-house-prices)).

- Higher interest rates increase borrowing costs, which can dampen housing demand and slow price growth.

### 2.2 Current Dynamics and Opportunities

- Despite rising inflation, mortgage rates have remained relatively low compared to historical norms. For instance, 30-year fixed mortgage rates increased modestly from 2.74% to 3.07% in 2021, while inflation accelerated by over 6 percentage points ([Tucker, 2021](https://www.zillow.com/research/housing-demand-inflation-2021-29187/)).

- This divergence creates a "golden window" where borrowing costs are low in real terms (adjusted for inflation), making homeownership more attractive and serving as an inflation hedge.

- Fixed-rate mortgages protect homeowners from rising future interest costs, effectively locking in housing expenses even as inflation erodes the value of money ([Fox, 2021](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/12/23/rising-inflation-and-hot-housing-market-what-you-need-to-know.html)).

